Answer: The problem is that you are calling `moveToFirst` before the loop starts. This moves the cursor to the first row of the result set, which is why you are not seeing the last row. You should call `moveToFirst` inside the loop. Here is the corrected code:

```java
public void loadTrack() {
    SQLiteDatabase db1 = waypoints.getWritableDatabase();
    Cursor trackCursor = db1.query(TABLE_NAME, FROM, "trackidfk=1", null, null, null, ORDER_BY);

    while (trackCursor.moveToNext()) {
        trackCursor.moveToFirst(); // Move to the first row after each loop
        Double lat = trackCursor.getDouble(2);
        Double lon = trackCursor.getDouble(1);
        //overlay.addGeoPoint( new GeoPoint( (int)(lat*1E6),  (int)(lon*1E6)));
        System.out.println(lon);
        System.out.println(lat);
    }
}
```

This way, the cursor will move to the first row after each loop, and you should see all the rows in your result set.

Please note that if you call `moveToFirst` inside the loop, it will move the cursor to the first row after each loop, which means you will only see the first row of the result set in each loop. If you want to see all rows in the result set, you should call `moveToNext` inside the loop.

Also, please ensure that your query is correct and returns the expected results. If the query is not returning the expected results, the issue might not be with the while loop.

